insert an invalid ConstantRange where the computed High bound is not strictly
greater than the Low bound. The reproducer uses a memset with a very large
positive GEP offset and a small nonzero size, which causes signed 64-bit addition
to overflow when computing the upper bound of the access range.\n\n2. Analyzing
opt's Log:\nThe stack trace points to getArgumentAccessInfo in
FunctionAttrs.cpp:712, which builds ConstantRangeLists for accesses and inserts
them. The helper lambda GetConstantIntRange (lines 674-685) constructs
ConstantRange for memsets/memcpys with constant length by computing [Offset,
Offset + Length) using signed APInt arithmetic, but it lacks overflow checks. In
contrast, GetTypeAccessRange (lines 658-673) does signed addition via sadd_ov and
bails on overflow. The memset case hits GetConstantIntRange and then insert,
triggering the assertion.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn GetConstantIntRange,
High is constructed as APInt(64, *Offset + ConstantLength->getSExtValue(), true)
without checking for signed overflow. For the reproducer, Offset =
9223372036854775805 (2^63-3), Length = 3, so Offset + Length =
9223372036854775808, which overflows signed 64-bit. Creating APInt with 'true'
(signed) from the overflowing sum wraps High to a negative value, making High <=
Low. When inserting this ConstantRange(Low, High), ConstantRangeList asserts that
Lower.slt(Upper), and the assertion fails.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit
the lambda GetConstantIntRange (lines 674-685) to mirror the overflow-safe
pattern used in GetTypeAccessRange. Specifically:\n- Build Low as APInt(64,
*Offset, true).\n- Build Len as APInt(64, ConstantLength->getSExtValue(),
